<p><font color="#000000" size="2" face="Arial">By Harriette Condes-Zervakis<br />
</font><font color="#000000" size="2" face="Arial"><br />
May 19 has been established as a day of remembrance around the world for the thousands of victims of the Pontian Genocide. In conjunction with this day of remembrance, each year the The Pontian Greek Society of Chicago, with the support from other Greek-American organizations, hosts a commemorative event to keep alive the memories of those who were victims of &quot;ethnic cleansing&quot; during the first half of the twentieth century. </font><font color="#000000" size="2" face="Arial"><a title="" href="/images/media_files/PDF_Documents/greekstarjune1109.pdf"><br />
<br />
Read entire article</a> <font size="1">[Adobe Acrobat PDF - 1.83 MB]</font></font></p>
<div align="justify"><font color="#000000"><em><br />
Above article first appeared in the Thursday, June 11 2009 issue of</em> The Greek Star. <em>Courtesy of </em>The Greek Star<em> editor, Diane Adam.&nbsp; </em></font></div>
